Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that lets an OCaml program

```ocaml
Blocksci.init "/path/to/blocksci/db" ;
Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
  Printf.printf "height=%Ld hash=%s time=%f\n"
    (Blocksci.block_height blk)
    (Blocksci.block_hash blk)
    (Blocksci.block_timestamp blk))
```

walk the whole blockchain.  

The binding consists of

* `blocksci.mli` – the public OCaml interface (what the user sees)  
* `blocksci_stubs.cpp` – the C‑C++ glue code that talks to BlockSci and the OCaml runtime  

Both files are shown together; you can copy‑paste them into a directory called `blocksci/`.  
A short `Makefile` snippet at the end shows how to compile them with `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt`.

---  
## 1. `blocksci.mli` – public OCaml API

```ocaml
(** {1 BlockSci OCaml bindings} *)

(** Opaque type that represents a single block.  The value is created by
    the iterator and must not be freed by the user.  It contains the
    fields exposed by the accessors below. *)
type block

(** Initialise the BlockSci database.  Must be called before any other
    function.  The argument is the path to the BlockSci data directory. *)
val init : string -> unit

(** Release all resources allocated by {!init}.  After calling this
    function the process can safely exit or re‑initialise a different
    database. *)
val close : unit -> unit

(** [iter_blocks f] walks the whole blockchain, calling [f blk] for each
    block.  The callback runs in the OCaml runtime, so it may allocate,
    raise exceptions, etc.  If the callback raises, iteration stops and
    the exception propagates to the caller of [iter_blocks]. *)
val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit

(** Accessors for the fields stored inside a [block] value. *)

val block_height    : block -> int64
(** Height (i.e. the block number) as a signed 64‑bit integer. *)

val block_hash      : block -> string
(** Hexadecimal block hash (exactly 64 characters for Bitcoin). *)

val block_timestamp : block -> float
(** Unix time (seconds since the epoch) as a floating point number. *)
```

